  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="page-wrapper">
        <p class="lead">You don't need a professional event planner or a massive budget to create a memorable sports banquet atmosphere. With a little creativity and some smart choices, you can transform a plain banquet hall into a celebration that feels special.</p>

        <p>Here are 15 decoration ideas that work for any sport, any venue, and any budget.</p>

        <h2>Table Decor (Biggest Visual Impact)</h2>

        <h3>1. Custom Sport Centerpieces</h3>
        <p>The single biggest bang for your decoration buck. A custom 3D printed football, basketball, soccer ball, or volleyball in your team's colors on every table instantly ties the room together. These also double as take-home keepsakes for seniors or special guests.</p>

        <h3>2. Team Color Linens</h3>
        <p>Rent tablecloths in your primary team color. Even a $2-3 per table rental charge transforms the room dramatically. If your budget is $0, ask each family to bring a tablecloth in the team color.</p>

        <h3>3. Photo Table Tents</h3>
        <p>Print 4x6 action photos of each athlete, fold them into tent cards, and place one at each seat. Costs pennies per player and every family searches for their athlete's photo.</p>

        <h3>4. Team Banner Tablescape</h3>
        <p>Hang your team banners along one wall or behind the head table. Add pennants, championship flags, or handmade signs from the student section.</p>

        <h3>5. Mason Jar Centerpieces</h3>
        <p>Fill mason jars with team-colored flowers, fake turf, or sand in school colors. Wrap the jar with ribbon in your team colors. Inexpensive and looks polished.</p>

        <h2>Room Decor</h2>

        <h3>6. Season Timeline Wall</h3>
        <p>Create a wall display with photos from the first practice to the final game. Add captions, stats, and memorable quotes. Guests will spend the whole evening walking through it.</p>

        <h3>7. Banner Drop</h3>
        <p>Order a large banner with the team name, season year, and a slogan. Hang it above the head table or at the entrance. Costs around $20-40 and anchors the room.</p>

        <h3>8. Balloon Arches in Team Colors</h3>
        <p>A balloon arch at the entrance costs surprisingly little if you assemble it yourself (YouTube tutorials make it easy). Use 2-3 shades of your team colors.</p>

        <h3>9. Senior Tribute Table</h3>
        <p>Dedicate a table to each senior with their photo, jersey, and a short note. Families love this, and it gives them a place to gather before the ceremony starts.</p>

        <h3>10. Spotlight on the Awards Table</h3>
        <p>Place the awards table in a prominent location with extra lighting. Arrange trophies, medals, and centerpieces at different heights using boxes or risers covered in fabric.</p>

        <h2>DIY Budget Ideas (Under $10 Each)</h2>

        <h3>11. Team Logo Projector</h3>
        <p>Use a simple projector to display the team logo or season highlights on a wall during dinner. Free if your school has a projector.</p>

        <h3>12. Jersey Table Runners</h3>
        <p>Ask players to bring their game jerseys. Lay them flat down the center of each table as a runner. Personal, free, and very cool.</p>

        <h3>13. Confetti Tablescape</h3>
        <p>Scatter team-colored confetti, small pom poms, or star confetti across tables. Costs a few dollars per table at any party supply store.</p>

        <h3>14. Sports Equipment Decor</h3>
        <p>Borrow game balls, helmets, or equipment from the team. Display them on tables or shelves around the room. Free and authentic.</p>

        <h3>15. Thank You Banner for Seniors</h3>
        <p>Have underclassmen sign a large banner with messages for the seniors. Display it at the banquet, then give it to the seniors as a keepsake.</p>

